    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "garden goblin stress?? lol what do u mean by that? i dont see any creatures in my yard. is it a specific disease or something?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Don't be fooled by the \"garden goblin\" moniker - it's just a colloquialism I use to describe the stress that can come with growing plants. But, if I'm being completely honest, I think it's a bit like the way a goblin might feel when they're stuck in a dungeon with no way out. Your plants are just trying to survive and thrive, but sometimes they need a little help navigating the complexities of the garden.\n\nThat being said, if you're looking for a more literal explanation, it's possible that your plants are suffering from a condition called \"interveinal chlorosis,\" where the veins on the underside of the leaves turn yellow due to a lack of nutrients. Or maybe it's a case of \"chlorosis\" caused by a fungal infection, which can also cause yellowing leaves.\n\nBut, let's get back to the garden goblin analogy - if your plants are feeling stressed, maybe it's time to give them a little \"goblin's luck\" boost with some extra care and attention. A balanced fertilizer, some pruning to promote healthy growth, and a bit of TLC might just do the trick to get your plants back on track.",
